{"id":"physics/0205011","submitter":"Jian-Miin Liu","authors":"Jian-Miin Liu","title":"Motivations to modify special relativity","comments":"5 pages with no figure","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  In the framework of special relativity, all particles are point-like or\nstring-like. This nature of particles has caused the divergence difficulties in\nquantum field, string and superstring theories. In the framework of special\nrelativity, due to the non-uniformity of the m-space and phase space in the\nusual inertial coordinate system, Boltzmann's hypothesis of the equality of the\nprobability of equal volume element is no longer appropriate. That makes it\nvery difficult to construct Lorentz-invariant statistical mechanics and\nthermodynamics for many-particle systems. Besides, some observations on special\nrelativity itself and its experimental facts are also reported. The conclusions\nfrom these observations are: Special relativity is not an ultimate theory; Some\nmodification is needed; Any modification must not violate the constancy of the\nlight speed and the local Lorentz invariance; It seems that we have to change\nthe assumption on local structures of gravity-free space and time in special\nrelativity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 5 May 2002 23:19:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
